{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>By the way, apples are often harvested in the fall.; Have you tried the new vegan cafe downtown, it's really popular among the yoga crowd.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Michael picks a random subset of the complex numbers {1, ω, ω^2, …, ω^2017} where ω is a primitive 2018th root of unity. All subsets (including the empty set, whose sum is defined to be 0) are equally likely. If S is the sum of the elements in the chosen subset, what is the expected value of |S|^2?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Represent each element as ω^k (with k=0,1,...,2017) and let X_k be the indicator variable that ω^k is included in the subset (P(X_k = 1) = 1/2, P(X_k = 0) = 1/2). Hence, S = Σ (X_k * ω^k).\n2. Compute |S|^2 = S * (conjugate of S) = Σ_{k} X_k + Σ_{j≠k} X_j X_k ω^j (conjugate(ω^k)).\n3. Take expectation term by term. For the diagonal terms, E[X_k] = 1/2, so they contribute 2018*(1/2).\n4. For the off-diagonal terms, independence gives E[X_j X_k] = (1/2)*(1/2)= 1/4. Thus, the sum of off-diagonals is (1/4) Σ_{j≠k} ω^(j-k).\n5. Note that the double sum over all indices (including j=k) is Σ_{j,k} ω^(j-k) = |Σ_{k} ω^k|^2. As ω are roots of unity, Σ_{k=0}^{2017} ω^k = 0, so |Σ ω^k|^2 = 0. Therefore, Σ_{j≠k} ω^(j-k) = -Σ_{k} ω^0 = -2018.\n6. Combining these, E[|S|^2] = (2018/2) + (1/4)(-2018) = (2018/2) - (2018/4) = 2018/4 = 1009/2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1009/2</answer>"
}

