  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Three distinct vertices are randomly selected among the five vertices of a regular pentagon. Let p be the probability that the triangle formed by the selected vertices is acute. Compute 10p.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Total number of triangles from 5 vertices is C(5,3) = 10.\\n2. For a triangle inscribed in a circle, it is acute if and only if none of its arcs (the intercepted arcs between consecutive vertices along the circle) is 180° or more. In a regular pentagon, the central angle between consecutive vertices is 72°. Thus, if any gap corresponds to 3 or more steps (i.e. 3×72° = 216°), the triangle is obtuse.\\n3. Labeling the vertices 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 in order, list all triangles and determine the gaps (in terms of steps between vertices, taken cyclically):\\n   - Triangle (1,2,3): gaps of 1, 1, and 3 → obtuse.\\n   - Triangle (1,2,4): gaps of 1, 2, and 2 → acute.\\n   - Triangle (1,2,5): gaps of 1, 3, and 1 → obtuse.\\n   - Triangle (1,3,4): gaps of 2, 1, and 2 → acute.\\n   - Triangle (1,3,5): gaps of 2, 2, and 1 → acute.\\n   - Triangle (1,4,5): gaps of 3, 1, and 1 → obtuse.\\n   - Triangle (2,3,4): gaps of 1, 1, and 3 → obtuse.\\n   - Triangle (2,3,5): gaps of 1, 2, and 2 → acute.\\n   - Triangle (2,4,5): gaps of 2, 1, and 2 → acute.\\n   - Triangle (3,4,5): gaps of 1, 1, and 3 → obtuse.\\n4. Count of acute triangles = 5.\\n5. Therefore, p = 5/10 = 1/2, and 10p = 10*(1/2) = 5.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>5</answer>"
}

