{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you know that the new coffee shop downtown offers a loyalty program that rewards customers with a free drink after every five purchases?\", \"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has an amazing brunch buffet on weekends?\", \"At twelve o ’ clock , when the church bells 464 start fritter chiming ,\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Ten gangsters are standing on a flat surface and the distances between every pair are all distinct. At twelve o’clock, each gangster fatally shoots the one among the other nine who is nearest. What is the minimum number of gangsters that will be killed?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Represent the situation as a directed graph where each vertex (gangster) has exactly one outgoing edge pointing to its unique nearest neighbor. A vertex is killed if it has at least one incoming edge.\n2. To minimize the number of gangsters killed, we must minimize the number of vertices that are shot (i.e. that have positive in-degrees). In the plane, it is a known geometric fact that any point can be the nearest neighbor of at most 5 other points (this is related to the kissing number in the plane with the condition of distinct distances).\n3. Since there are 10 gangsters, there are 10 directed edges. If we let k be the number of gangsters that get shot, then the total number of incoming edges is at most 5 per gangster, so we must have 10 ≤ 5k, which implies k ≥ 2.\n4. Lastly, we verify that a configuration achieving k = 2 is indeed possible. For example, partition the gangsters into two groups. Designate two gangsters A and B such that A and B are mutual nearest neighbors (each shooting the other). Then arrange the remaining 8 gangsters so that exactly 4 of them have A as their nearest neighbor and the other 4 have B as their nearest neighbor. This way, A and B each receive 1 (from each other) plus 4 additional incoming edges, reaching the maximum allowed 5, and the remaining gangsters receive no shots. Thus, only gangsters A and B are killed.\n5. Therefore, the minimum number of gangsters that will be killed is 2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown has a great selection of organic tea?\", \"Did you know that the newest restaurant in town has a unique menu item called \\\"Dragon's Breath\\\" that's essentially a spicy chicken wing?\", \"( Gregory Galperin )\", \"574\", \"464 square toes\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider the square grid in the Euclidean plane given by all points (m, n) with m and n integers. Is it possible to cover every grid point (i.e. have each one lie in the interior of one of the discs) by an infinite family of discs with non‐overlapping interiors if each disc has radius at least 5?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. The grid has a point at every integer coordinate so its density is 1 point per unit area.\n2. Suppose we have an infinite family of discs, each with radius at least 5; so each disc covers an area of at least A_disk = π × 5^2 = 25π. However, the discs are required to have non-overlapping interiors. In a packing of equal (or similarly sized) objects in the plane, a lower bound on the spacing exists – roughly, centers of discs of radius 5 must be separated by at least 10 in many cases.\n3. Consider a large square region of area R (say, side length L so that R ≈ L^2) that contains about L^2 grid points. Because the discs in the covering are disjoint, a maximal packing argument shows that the number of discs that can have their centers in this region is at most on the order of L^2/(10^2) = L^2/100 (up to boundary effects).\n4. Therefore, the maximum area covered by these discs within the region is roughly (number of discs) × (area per disc) ≈ (L^2/100) × 25π = (25π/100)L^2 = (π/4)L^2. Note that π/4 ≈ 0.785, so these discs can cover at most about 78.5% of the area of the region.\n5. Since grid points are uniformly distributed (density 1 per unit area), even under the best circumstances the union of the non-overlapping discs could cover at most about 78.5% of the grid points in a large region. Hence, many grid points must remain uncovered.\n6. This density argument implies that it is impossible to cover every lattice point (i.e. have every grid point in the interior of some disc) using an infinite collection of non-overlapping discs of radius at least 5.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>No, it is not possible.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Has anyone seen the latest episode of that new sci‐fi show everyone's been talking about?\", \"947 (in the phrase 'a pentagon ABCDE is 947 circumscribed about a circle')\", \"pass with flying colors and equal measuring stick to (in the phrase about the angles at the vertices)\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has a really cute cat that always greets customers at the door.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A pentagon ABCDE is circumscribed about a circle. The interior angles at vertices A, C, and E are each 100°. (Since the sum of the interior angles of a pentagon is 540°, the remaining two angles at vertices B and D are 120° each.) Find the measure of the angle ∠ACE.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Note that the sum of the interior angles of a pentagon is 540°. With angles A, C, and E given as 100° each, we have A + C + E = 300°. Hence, the remaining two angles, at B and D, must sum to 540° - 300° = 240°. By symmetry (or by given information in a tangential pentagon with these properties), we deduce that B = D = 120°.\nStep 2: Observe that in a tangential pentagon the incircle touches every side and the angle bisectors of the vertices are concurrent at the incenter. In our pentagon, the vertices A, C, and E each have an angle of 100° so their angle bisectors divide these angles into equal 50° angles.\nStep 3: Consider triangle ACE formed by alternating vertices. In many such tangential pentagons, a notable property is that the vertex angles of triangle ACE can be expressed in terms of the other vertex angles of the pentagon. In fact, one may establish that the measure of ∠ACE is given by 180° minus half the sum of the angles at B and D. (This can be seen from the fact that drawing the diagonals from C to A and C to E, and considering the tangency and symmetry properties of the incircle, yields an angle at C which is the supplement to half the sum of the “gaps” between A and E along the circle).\nStep 4: Since B and D are 120° each, we have (B + D)/2 = (120° + 120°)/2 = 240°/2 = 120°. Hence, ∠ACE = 180° - 120° = 60°.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>60°</answer>"
}

{
