  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For how many integers a with 1 ≤ a ≤ 10 is a^(2014) + a^(2015) divisible by 5?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Factor the expression: a^(2014) + a^(2015) = a^(2014) * (1 + a). \n2. For the product a^(2014)*(1+a) to be divisible by 5, at least one of the factors must be divisible by 5. \n3. Check if a^(2014) is divisible by 5. Since a^(2014) is divisible by 5 if a is divisible by 5, in the range 1 to 10, a = 5 and a = 10 work. \n4. Next, check if (1+a) is divisible by 5. This requires a ≡ 4 (mod 5). In the range 1 to 10, a = 4 and a = 9 satisfy this. \n5. Verify that there is no overlap between the two cases (the numbers {5,10} and {4,9} are distinct). \n6. Count the total: 2 (from the first case) + 2 (from the second case) = 4.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>4</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new coffee shop downtown is offering a buy-one-get-one‐free deal on their signature lattes all weekend.; The new coffee shop downtown has a really cool mural on the wall.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For any two different real numbers x and y, define D(x, y) to be the unique integer d satisfying 2^d ≤ |x − y| < 2^(d+1). Given a set of real numbers F and, for each x in F, let the scales of x in F be the set of values { D(x, y) : y in F, y ≠ x }. Let k be a given positive integer. Suppose that every element x of F has at most k different scales. What is the maximum possible size of F?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We are given that for each x in F, the differences |x − y| (for y ≠ x) fall into at most k distinct dyadic intervals, that is, intervals of the form [2^d, 2^(d+1)). Intuitively, if the set F has many elements then for a given x the distances to the other points are likely to “spread out” over many orders of magnitude. The condition forces a strong restriction on the configuration of F. One may show (for example, by an inductive doubling argument or a combinatorial pigeon‐hole argument on the intervals into which the differences fall) that F cannot have more than 2^k elements. In fact, one may construct an example of a set F with exactly 2^k points satisfying the condition. (For instance, a carefully chosen set where the differences between elements occur in only k different dyadic scales will do.)\n\nThus, the maximum possible size of F is 2^k.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^k</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown is offering a special discount on their brunch menu on Sundays?\", \"I wish I could remember the name of that new bakery that just opened up downtown, I've been meaning to try their croissants all week.\"</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>We have n coins, one of which is fake and differs in weight from the genuine coins. We also have a two‐pan balance that works reliably (i.e. shows the correct result) when the weights on the pans differ, but if the pans are balanced it may show an arbitrary outcome. For what maximum value of n (in terms of k, the maximum allowed weighings) can we determine which coin is fake and whether it is lighter or heavier than the genuine coins in at most k weighings?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: In the counterfeit coin problem, there are 2n possible scenarios (each coin could be fake and it could be either heavier or lighter). \nStep 2: A weighing on a two‐pan scale has three possible outcomes. With k weighings, in principle we can have up to 3^k different outcome sequences. \nStep 3: To guarantee that every possibility is uniquely distinguishable, we need 3^k >= 2n + a gap needed to rule out ambiguous cases. In the classic coin weighing problem (without any extra artificial outcomes in the balanced case) a tighter analysis shows that the maximum number of coins that can be processed in k weighings is given by n = (3^k - 3)/2. \nStep 4: Checking for k = 3: (27 - 3)/2 = 12, which is consistent with the well‐known 12-coin problem. \nThus, the answer is n = (3^k - 3)/2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>n = (3^k - 3)/2</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"574\", \"funfair\", \"876\", \"The amount of coffee I drank this morning is equivalent to the weight of a small cat.\", \"I've been meaning to ask you, have you tried that new pasta dish at Bella Vita?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A fair coin is flipped eight times in a row. Let p be the probability that there is exactly one pair of consecutive flips that are both heads and exactly one pair of consecutive flips that are both tails. If p = a/b, where a and b are relatively prime positive integers, compute 100a + b.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Total outcomes for 8 coin flips = 2^8 = 256.\\n2. A pair of consecutive heads (HH) or tails (TT) occurs within ‘runs’ in the sequence. In any run of identical flips of length L, there are L - 1 consecutive pairs. To have exactly one HH pair, the runs of heads must consist only of single H’s except one that is a run of 2 H’s (since a run of length 2 gives exactly 1 pair) and similarly for tails.\\n3. If we denote each run as having length 1 by default and a run of length 2 as contributing an extra flip, then the total length equals (number of runs) + (number of runs of length 2). We need exactly 1 extra flip for heads and 1 extra for tails, so in total 2 extra flips. Let r be the total number of runs. Then we have r + 2 = 8, so r = 6.\\n4. The sequence must therefore be divided into 6 runs, and the runs alternate between H and T. There are 2 cases depending on the first flip:\\n   - Case A: Sequence starts with H. Then the runs are H, T, H, T, H, T. There are 3 H runs and 3 T runs. We choose 1 out of the 3 H runs to be of length 2 and 1 out of the 3 T runs to be of length 2. That gives 3 * 3 = 9 sequences.\\n   - Case B: Sequence starts with T. Then the runs are T, H, T, H, T, H. Again, 3 T runs and 3 H runs, and the number of ways similarly is 3 * 3 = 9.\\n5. Total favorable sequences = 9 + 9 = 18.\\n6. Therefore, the probability p = 18/256 = 9/128 (after dividing numerator and denominator by 2). Thus, a = 9 and b = 128.\\n7. Finally, compute 100a + b = 100*9 + 128 = 900 + 128 = 1028.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1028</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The weather in Paris has been quite gloomy lately.\", \"Have you tried that new coffee shop downtown?\", \"574 ;\", \"464 okay\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>The line with equation y = 2x - 6 is translated upwards by 4 units. What is the x-intercept of the resulting line?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. The original equation is y = 2x - 6. Translating the line upward by 4 units means adding 4 to the y-values, resulting in the equation: y = 2x - 6 + 4, which simplifies to y = 2x - 2.\n2. To find the x-intercept, set y = 0 and solve for x: 0 = 2x - 2 => 2x = 2 => x = 1.\n3. Thus, the x-intercept of the translated line is the point where x = 1, i.e., (1, 0).",
  "final_answer": "<answer>(1, 0)</answer>"
}

