{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new coffee shop downtown has an amazing selection of artisanal muffins.\", \"Did you know that the average lifespan of a koala is around 10-15 years in the wild?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>An airline operates flights between any two capital cities in the European Union. Each flight has a fixed price, and the price is the same in both directions. Furthermore, for any given city the flights leaving from that city have pairwise distinct prices. Anna and Bella wish to visit each city exactly once (they may start at different cities). At each step, from her current city, Anna always takes the cheapest flight to a city she has not yet visited, while Bella always takes the most expensive such flight. Is it true that Bella’s tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna’s tour?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Observe that the problem takes place on a complete graph where every pair of cities is connected by a flight whose cost does not depend on the direction, and at each city the outgoing edges have distinct costs.\n2. Notice that both Anna and Bella construct a Hamiltonian path (or tour if they return to the start) by the greedy rule, but using opposite extremes: Anna always picks the minimum cost available edge at her current city and Bella always picks the maximum cost available edge at her current city.\n3. At each city the set of available edges has a minimum and a maximum; clearly, the maximum is at least as high as the minimum. However, because the tours can visit cities in different orders, one must show that no matter how the choices later restrict the available flights, each local decision made by Bella is at least as ‘expensive’ (or higher in cost) as the decision Anna could have made from the same set.\n4. One common way to justify the claim is by a pairwise comparison argument. Imagine that if both travelers were placed in the same city with the same set S of available flights, then Bella’s rule chooses the edge with maximum cost b and Anna’s chooses the edge with minimum cost a, with b ≥ a. Although their subsequent journeys may differ, one can inductively argue that at every step the decision made by Bella is not less costly than the one Anna makes from the same situation. Thus, summing over the steps, Bella’s overall tour cost is at least as high as Anna’s.\n5. Therefore, under the rules given, it is indeed true that Bella’s tour will always cost at least as much as Anna’s tour.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, it is true that Bella's tour will surely cost at least as much as Anna's tour.</answer>"
}

