{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new café on Main Street has a lovely patio area perfect for a relaxing afternoon with a good book.\", \"574\", \"464\", \"Did you know that the new restaurant downtown has an amazing brunch menu?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let f(x) = x^4 + ax^3 + bx^2 + cx + d be a polynomial whose roots are all negative integers. If a + b + c + d = 2009, find d.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Since all roots are negative integers, let the roots be -p, -q, -r, -s where p, q, r, s are positive integers. Then the polynomial can be written as f(x) = (x + p)(x + q)(x + r)(x + s). \nStep 2: When expanded, the coefficients are: a = p + q + r + s, b = (sum of products of pairs), c = (sum of products of triples), and d = p*q*r*s.\nStep 3: Note that f(1) = 1 + a + b + c + d. Given a + b + c + d = 2009, we obtain f(1) = 2010.\nStep 4: Also, f(1) = (1 + p)(1 + q)(1 + r)(1 + s) = 2010. Factor 2010 = 2 * 3 * 5 * 67.\nStep 5: Since p, q, r, s are positive integers, it is natural to set (1+p, 1+q, 1+r, 1+s) equal to (2, 3, 5, 67) in some order. This gives: p = 1, q = 2, r = 4, s = 66.\nStep 6: Finally, d = p * q * r * s = 1 * 2 * 4 * 66 = 528.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>528</answer>"
}

