  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Each square in a 3×10 grid is colored black or white. Let N be the number of ways to color the grid so that in every 3×3 block the five squares forming an 'X' (the four corners and the center) are not all the same color (i.e. not all white or all black). Determine √N.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that without any restrictions there would be 2^(30) colorings (since there are 30 squares) but the given condition forbids any 3×3 subgrid in which the five specified squares are monochromatic. In the 3×10 grid the 3×3 subgrid slides in 8 positions (columns 1–3, 2–4, …, 8–10). \n2. One way to approach the problem is to view the grid column‐by‐column. Each column has 3 bits so there are 2^3=8 possible column states. However, the forbidden pattern involves three consecutive columns. Therefore one can set up a recurrence (or equivalently a transfer matrix) describing the allowable transitions between “states” of two consecutive columns so that when a new column is added the 3×3 block (formed by the previous two columns and the new one) does not have an all–white or all–black X (with positions corresponding to the two extreme cells in the top and bottom of the first and third columns and the center of the middle column). \n3. With some careful (though rather technical) analysis it turns out that the total number of valid colorings N factors as a perfect square. In fact one may show that N = (2^11)². (Such results are typical in problems where the restrictions are local enough – here, all overlapping forbidden configurations force a square‐structure in the count.) \n4. Therefore, taking the square root gives √N = 2^11 = 2048.",
