}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"Did you know that the latest season of your favorite TV show is now available on Netflix?\", \"The weather forecast for the upcoming weekend is looking quite unpredictable with a high chance of scattered thunderstorms.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let n be a positive integer. Find all n×n real matrices A that have only real eigenvalues and satisfy the equation A + A^k = A^T for some integer k ≥ n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Note that the equation is A + A^k = A^T, which can be rearranged to A^T - A = A^k. The left-hand side, A^T - A, is skew-symmetric (its transpose equals its negation). 2. Consequently, A^k must also be skew-symmetric. 3. Because A is given to have only real eigenvalues, any eigenvalue λ of A is real and so any eigenvalue of A^k is λ^k, which is also real. 4. For a skew-symmetric matrix, however, all eigenvalues are either 0 or purely imaginary. The only way for a real number to be purely imaginary is if it is 0. Thus, for every eigenvalue λ of A, we must have λ^k = 0, which forces λ = 0. 5. Hence, every eigenvalue of A is 0. This indicates that A is a nilpotent matrix. 6. Now observe that when k ≥ n, for any nilpotent n×n matrix A we have A^n = 0, so certainly A^k = 0. 7. Substituting A^k = 0 in the original equation gives A + 0 = A^T or A = A^T. 8. A symmetric (A = A^T) nilpotent matrix must be the zero matrix because all eigenvalues of a symmetric matrix are real and its only eigenvalue is 0. 9. Therefore, the only solution is A = 0.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>The only n×n real matrix A satisfying the given conditions is the zero matrix.</answer>"
}

