{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new restaurant downtown serves an amazing vegan chocolate cake.\", \"The cost of groceries has been increasing steadily over the past year.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>We say that a sequence (a₁, a₂, …) is called expansive if for all positive integers i and j with i < j, we have |aᵢ - aⱼ| ≥ 1/j. Find all positive real numbers C for which there exists an expansive sequence whose terms lie in the interval [0, C].</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: First, note that the definition forces a minimal separation between the first two terms. In particular, taking i = 1 and j = 2 gives |a₁ - a₂| ≥ 1/2. Thus any two points in [0, C] satisfying this must be at least 1/2 apart. This immediately implies that if an expansive sequence exists in [0, C] then C must be at least 1/2, since otherwise it would be impossible to place a₁ and a₂ with a separation of 1/2.\n\nStep 2: We now show that if C ≥ 1/2 then one can indeed construct an expansive sequence in [0, C]. The idea is that the requirement for later terms (for j ≥ 3) is weaker since the gap required is 1/j, which decreases to 0 as j increases. One may adopt a greedy procedure. For example, choose a₁ arbitrarily in [0, C] and let a₂ be a number in [0, C] at least 1/2 away from a₁. This is possible if C ≥ 1/2. Then for each subsequent term aⱼ (j ≥ 3), the condition is that aⱼ must be at least 1/j away from every previous term. Since 1/j is a small positive number and because [0, C] (with C at least 1/2) is a closed interval, one may pick aⱼ carefully (possibly by oscillating near one end or using a Cantor‐type construction) to satisfy the conditions. (A detailed construction can be given, but the key is that the only “hard” requirement is from the pair (a₁, a₂) which forces C ≥ 1/2.)\n\nStep 3: Combining the necessity (C must be at least 1/2) and the sufficiency (if C ≥ 1/2, an expansive sequence can be constructed), we conclude that the answer is: all positive real numbers C with C ≥ 1/2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>C ≥ 1/2</answer>"
}

