  "solution_steps": "1. Recognize the subtraction game: There are 30 matches and each player can take 1 to 6 matches per turn.\n2. A common winning strategy is to force the opponent into positions that are a multiple of (maximum move + 1), which in this case is 7, because no matter what move the opponent makes (between 1 and 6), you can always pick a number that brings the total taken in a round to 7.\n3. To guarantee a win, Alex should try and leave Bob with a multiple of 7 matches after his move. Let x be the number of matches Alex takes. Then the number of matches left is 30 - x. We require 30 - x to be a multiple of 7.\n4. Notice that 30 modulo 7 is 2 (since 7 × 4 = 28 and 30 - 28 = 2). Thus, we want x = 2 to leave 30 - 2 = 28 matches, and 28 is a multiple of 7.\n5. By taking 2 matches first, Alex can always respond to Bob’s moves by taking (7 - (number Bob takes)), thereby ensuring that after each round the number of matches remaining is a multiple of 7, and eventually forcing a win when he picks up the last match.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2</answer>"
