  "solution_steps": "1. Note that any line which does not meet the set of black cells has 0 black cells; the condition only concerns lines that intersect the black set. 2. For k = 1 one may take a single black cell. In this case each of the four lines (horizontal, vertical, and the two diagonal directions) that pass through that single cell contains exactly one black cell, while all other lines (which do not pass through it) have 0. Thus k = 1 is possible. 3. It turns out that with a much more involved construction one can build a finite set S of cells having the property that every horizontal, vertical, and diagonal line that meets S contains exactly 4 black cells (and lines disjoint from S contain 0). Several research papers in this area (by Dinev, Garov, Belukhov and others) have shown that aside from the trivial single‐cell configuration yielding k = 1, the only other possibility is k = 4. 4. A proof by contradiction (or an exhaustive analysis of possible configurations) shows that for any other k > 1, any finite black cell set would force the existence of a line with a number of black cells different from k. 5. Hence, the only values of k for which such a finite configuration exists are k = 1 and k = 4.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>k = 1 and k = 4</answer>"
