{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The new restaurant in town serves the best vegan sushi in the country.; The beach was particularly crowded on the day of the summer solstice.; Additionally, the extraneous numbers 521 and 887 and the garbled text in the set notation are irrelevant.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Consider all sequences of five letters formed from the set {T, U, R, N, I, P} with repetitions allowed, arranged in alphabetical order as in a dictionary. Two sequences are called anagrams of each other if one can be obtained by rearranging the letters of the other. How many pairs of anagrams are there (where the two sequences are distinct) that have exactly 100 other sequences between them in the dictionary?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Note that two sequences are anagrams if they use exactly the same multiset of letters. Since letters can repeat but we are dealing with pairs separated by exactly 100 intervening sequences in the overall dictionary order, a necessary condition is that the two sequences lie in the same anagram group.\nStep 2: For any given multiset (anagram group) of 5 letters, the two distinct sequences from that group will have positions (when all sequences from that group are arranged in increasing dictionary order) that are some distance apart. However, the gap of 101 in the overall dictionary order will occur only if the group's number of sequences is sufficiently large so that two of its members can be separated by 100 other sequences (i.e. their positions differ by 101).\nStep 3: The maximum size an anagram group can have is when all 5 letters are distinct. In that case, the number of distinct permutations is 5! = 120. For any anagram group of size 120, if we list its 120 members in order, a pair of members that have exactly 100 sequences between them must be chosen so that if the first one is in position i, the second is in position i+101. The first position i can then range from 1 to 120 − 101 = 19. Thus, each such group yields 19 valid pairs.\nStep 4: Consider which multisets give 120 sequences. They are exactly the multisets with 5 distinct letters. Since the letters come from the set {T, U, R, N, I, P} containing 6 letters, the number of ways to choose 5 distinct letters is C(6,5) = 6. (All other multisets with repeated letters would yield fewer than 120 sequences, and then it is impossible to have a gap of 101 because the total number in that group would be less than 102.)\nStep 5: Therefore, only the 6 groups of 5 distinct letters qualify. Each of these groups contributes 19 pairs with exactly 100 sequences in between. Multiplying gives 6 * 19 = 114.\nStep 6: Hence, the total number of pairs of anagrams with exactly 100 other sequences between them in the dictionary is 114.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>114</answer>"
}

