  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>An unfair coin has the property that when flipped 4 times, it has the same probability of turning up 2 heads and 2 tails (in any order) as 3 heads and 1 tail (in any order). What is the probability of getting a head in any one flip?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Let p be the probability of getting a head on a single flip. When the coin is flipped 4 times, the probability of 2 heads and 2 tails is calculated by: P(2 heads, 2 tails) = C(4,2) * p^2 * (1-p)^2 = 6 * p^2 * (1-p)^2. Similarly, the probability of 3 heads and 1 tail is: P(3 heads, 1 tail) = C(4,3) * p^3 * (1-p) = 4 * p^3 * (1-p). Since these probabilities are equal, we have: 6 * p^2 * (1-p)^2 = 4 * p^3 * (1-p). Assuming p is not 0 or 1, we can cancel p^2 and (1-p) from both sides to get: 6 * (1-p) = 4 * p. Solving for p, we have 6 - 6p = 4p, which implies 6 = 10p. Therefore, p = 6/10 = 3/5.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>3/5</answer>"
}

