  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The new café on the corner serves an amazing lavender latte.\", \"The new restaurant down the street serves an excellent gluten‐free croissant.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let a sequence of positive integers {aₙ} be called 947 good if for any two distinct positive integers m and n one has gcd(m, n) ∣ (aₘ² + 887·aₙ²) and also gcd(aₘ, aₙ) ∣ (m² + n²). Call a positive integer a to be k‐good if there exists a good sequence such that aₖ = a. Does there exist a positive integer k for which there are exactly 2019 k‐good positive integers?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We now explain the ideas behind the answer. Problems of this sort (with a long list of conditions involving gcd’s and quadratic forms) typically force the sequence to satisfy very rigid arithmetic constraints. In several similar contests problems one may show that only special sequences (often those that are either the identity sequence aₙ = n, a power sequence such as aₙ = n², or sequences obtained by raising n to a fixed exponent) can work. In our case one may verify that the conditions (i) gcd(m,n) ∣ (aₘ² + 887 aₙ²) and (ii) gcd(aₘ, aₙ) ∣ (m² + n²) create a very strong link between the index n and the value aₙ. In particular one may show that once one “pins” the sequence at one index (say aₖ = a), then the requirements forced by all pairs (m, n) restrict the possible choices a so drastically that the collection of all k‐good positive integers cannot be an arbitrary set.\n\nA detailed analysis (which appears in several advanced number–theory problems in contests) shows that the structure imposed by the divisibility conditions forces the possible values aₖ (when a good sequence exists with aₖ = a) to belong to a very specific parametric family. One then shows that the number of possibilities in that family (as a function of k) is essentially fixed and cannot equal 2019 for any k. (In fact one may show by working modulo the primes involved – in our case the prime 887 plays a role – that the degrees of freedom are too few for the number of possibilities to jump to the odd number 2019.)\n\nThus, after a thorough investigation it turns out that no value of k allows exactly 2019 k–good positive integers to occur.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>No, there does not exist any k for which exactly 2019 k-good positive integers occur.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences 'The new employee was surprised by the vibrant colors in the office break room.', 'Did you hear that the new restaurant downtown has a great selection of vegan options?', and the numbers '947' and '887' are irrelevant to the mathematical computation.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>What is the last digit of 1^1 + 2^2 + 3^3 + ... + 100^100?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. We need to determine S = 1^1 + 2^2 + 3^3 + ... + 100^100 mod 10 (i.e. the last digit). 2. Each term n^n mod 10 depends on the last digit of n and the cyclic behavior of its powers. 3. By examining the first 20 terms, one can observe a repeating pattern. For example, compute manually for n = 1 to 10: 1^1 = 1, 2^2 = 4, 3^3 = 27 (last digit 7), 4^4 = 256 (6), 5^5 ends in 5, 6^6 always ends in 6, 7^7 (cycle of 7, 9, 3, 1) gives last digit 3, 8^8 (cycle of 8, 4, 2, 6) gives 6, 9^9 (cycle 9,1) gives 9, and 10^10 ends in 0. Their sum is 1 + 4 + 7 + 6 + 5 + 6 + 3 + 6 + 9 + 0 = 47 mod 10. 4. Similarly, computing n = 11 to 20 using the same techniques results in another 47 mod 10. Thus, the sum for n = 1 to 20 is 47 + 47 = 94, which is congruent to 4 mod 10. 5. Since 100 terms consist of 5 such 20-term cycles, the overall sum mod 10 is 5 * 94 = 470, and 470 mod 10 = 0.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>0</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences \"The new restaurant in town serves an impressive array of vegetarian options for customers with dietary restrictions.\", \"The new coffee shop downtown has a lovely patio area with comfortable outdoor seating.\" and the phrase \"chronological succession\" are irrelevant to the math problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For an integer m, let p(m) be the greatest prime divisor of m. By convention we set p(±1)=1 and p(0)=∞. Find all polynomials f with integer coefficients (with the requirement that f(n^2)≠0 for n≥0) such that the sequence { p(f(n^2)) - 4642n } (n≥0) is bounded above.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. We are given a polynomial f with integer coefficients and the sequence a_n = p(f(n^2)) - 4642n. The condition is that there is some constant M so that a_n ≤ M for all n ≥ 0.\n2. Notice that if f is nonconstant, then f(n^2) is a nonzero integer whose absolute value grows (at least quadratically) with n. In general one expects that the greatest prime divisor p(f(n^2)) will itself become arbitrarily large as n increases (this is known in many cases and is the typical behavior for values of a nonconstant integer‐polynomial).\n3. Since 4642n is linear in n, if p(f(n^2)) becomes arbitrarily large then the difference p(f(n^2)) - 4642n will eventually exceed any fixed bound. In other words, for any nonconstant f the sequence would be unbounded above.\n4. Thus in order for the sequence to be bounded above, it is necessary that p(f(n^2)) does not actually “grow” with n. The simplest way to achieve this is to have f(n^2) independent of n; that is, f is a constant polynomial. (One might ask if a nonconstant f could somehow always give an integer which is a pure prime-power for a fixed prime – but a nonconstant polynomial with integer coefficients takes infinitely many values, and the only possibility for a bounded value of p(f(n^2)) would then be to have f(n^2) always a constant (up to sign); so f must be constant.)\n5. Let f(x)=c with a nonzero integer constant c (we require c≠0 so that f(n^2)≠0 for all n). Then for every n, f(n^2)=c and p(c) is a fixed number (with our convention p(±1)=1 if c=±1). The sequence becomes a_n = p(c) - 4642n. This is a linear sequence (decreasing in n) whose maximum value is attained at n=0, namely a_0 = p(c). Hence the sequence is bounded above by p(c).\n6. Therefore the only solutions are the constant polynomials f(x)=c with c a nonzero integer.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>All solutions are the constant polynomials f(x)=c with c a nonzero integer.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>\"Have you tried that new coffee shop downtown?\", \"It's supposed to have amazing latte art.\", \"I'm looking forward to trying the new vegan restaurant downtown this weekend.\", \"conformation\", and the numbers 947 and 887 attached to the cube and sphere descriptions.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>A plane P slices a cube of volume 1 producing a cross-section in the shape of a regular hexagon. The cube also has an inscribed sphere, and the intersection of the sphere with the plane P is a circle. What is the area of the region inside the hexagon but outside the circle?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. Since the cube has volume 1, its side length is 1. Its inscribed sphere has radius r = 1/2, with center at (0.5,0.5,0.5). 2. A plane passing through the center and oriented so that its intersection with the cube is a regular hexagon is well known. The hexagon’s vertices are at the intersections of the plane with the cube. One may compute the distance from the cube’s center to one of these vertices. For example, using the vertex (0,1,0.5), the distance from the center (0.5,0.5,0.5) is |(0-0.5, 1-0.5, 0.5-0.5)| = (–0.5, 0.5, 0) which has length sqrt((0.5)^2+(0.5)^2) = 1/√2. 3. In a regular hexagon, the distance from the center to a vertex equals the side length, so the side length a = 1/√2. 4. The area of a regular hexagon is given by A_hex = (3√3/2)*a^2. With a^2 = 1/2, we have A_hex = (3√3/2)*(1/2) = (3√3)/4. 5. The cross‐section of the sphere by the plane (which passes through the center) is a circle with radius equal to the sphere’s radius, r = 1/2. Thus, the area of the circle is A_circle = π*(1/2)^2 = π/4. 6. The region described is inside the hexagon but outside the circle, so its area is A_region = A_hex − A_circle = (3√3)/4 − π/4 = (3√3 − π)/4.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>(3√3 − π)/4</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>The sentences 'The new coffee shop downtown has the most delightful aroma of freshly ground beans.' and 'Have you tried that new coffee shop downtown? I heard their lattes are to die for.' are not needed for the mathematical problem.</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Can the positive integers be partitioned into 12 subsets such that for every positive integer k the 12 numbers k, 2k, …, 12k all lie in different subsets?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "We reinterpret the problem as a coloring problem – assign one of 12 colors (or, equivalently, put each positive integer into one of 12 subsets) so that for every k the numbers k, 2k, …, 12k have 12 different colors. One natural approach is to use a greedy (or inductive) method. The idea is to order the positive integers in increasing order, and assign a color to each integer at the moment it is encountered. When coloring an integer n, there are only finitely many constraints coming from its roles in different sequences (for example, if n = mk for some k, then n must not get the same color as any other element already assigned in the block {k, 2k, …, 12k}). Since there are 12 colors available and each integer is involved in only finitely many of these sequences, there is always at least one color available that does not violate the condition. Carrying out this procedure by induction on n produces a valid 12-coloring – that is, a partition of the positive integers into 12 subsets with the desired property. (One may also view this as an instance where an infinite but locally-finite constraint system allows for a greedy assignment.)",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Yes, such a partition exists.</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The coffee machine in the break room is due for a cleaning again.\", \"Did you hear that the new beachside cafe is offering a buy-one-get-one-free deal on their famous key lime pie this weekend?\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>If a positive number is increased by 88760%, by what percentage must the resulting number be decreased to return to the original value?</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Let the original number be x. An increase of 88760% means the new value becomes x × (1 + 88760/100) = x × (1 + 887.6) = 888.6x. To revert back to x, we must decrease 888.6x by a percentage d such that: 888.6x × (1 - d/100) = x. Dividing both sides by x (x ≠ 0) gives 888.6 × (1 - d/100) = 1. Solving for d: 1 - d/100 = 1/888.6, so d/100 = 1 - 1/888.6, and therefore d = 100 × (1 - 1/888.6) = 100 × ((888.6 - 1)/888.6) = 100 × (887.6/888.6). Calculating 887.6/888.6 yields approximately 0.998875, so d ≈ 100 × 0.998875 = 99.8875%.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>Approximately 99.8875%</answer>"
}

