{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>My grandmother's cat could recite the entire script of \"Hamlet\" backwards while riding a unicycle.; Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is having a buy-one-get-one-free promotion on all their seasonal lattes this weekend?</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Find the number of nonempty families F of subsets of the set {1, 2, ..., 2014} such that (a) for any subsets S1, S2 in F, the intersection S1 ∩ S2 is in F, and (b) if S is in F and S ⊆ T ⊆ {1, 2, ..., 2014}, then T is in F.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "1. A family F of subsets that is closed under intersections (condition a) and is upward closed (condition b) is exactly a filter on the set {1, 2, ..., 2014}. 2. In any such nonempty family F, if we take I = ⋂{S : S ∈ F}, then I is the unique minimal element of F (i.e. I ⊆ S for all S in F). 3. Due to upward closure, every subset T with I ⊆ T must be in F. Hence, F = {T ⊆ {1, 2, ..., 2014} : I ⊆ T}. 4. Conversely, for any subset I ⊆ {1,2,...,2014} (including the possibility I = ∅), the collection F(I) = {T ⊆ {1,2,...,2014} : I ⊆ T} is a valid family satisfying the conditions. 5. Because each valid family is uniquely determined by its minimal element I, and there are exactly 2^(2014) subsets of {1, 2, ..., 2014}, there are 2^(2014) such families F.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>2^(2014)</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>[\"The recent rainfall has been causing some flooding in the nearby park.\", \"The new artisanal coffee shop downtown has the best lavender latte in the city.\"]</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>For each positive integer n, let s(n) be the sum of the squares of the digits of n. For example, s(15)=1^2+5^2=26. Determine all integers n ≥ 1 such that s(n) = n.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Notice that for a k-digit number n, the maximum value of s(n) (which is the sum of the squares of its digits) is 81k (since each digit squared is at most 9^2 = 81). Meanwhile, n is at least 10^(k-1). For k ≥ 2, we have 10^(k-1) > 81k. This means that for numbers with two or more digits, n will always be greater than s(n). Thus any potential solution must be a one-digit number.\n\nStep 2: For a one-digit number n (with n = d, where 1 ≤ d ≤ 9), s(n) = d^2. We require d^2 = d, which leads to the equation d(d - 1) = 0. The solutions to this equation are d = 0 or d = 1. Since n must be at least 1, only d = 1 is valid.\n\nStep 3: Therefore, the only integer n ≥ 1 satisfying s(n) = n is n = 1.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>1</answer>"
}

