  "final_answer": "<answer>7</answer>"
}

{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>1. 'The new coffee shop downtown has an impressive selection of artisanal teas.' 2. '521 ; prevent' in the description of the matrix. 3. '[ hide= '' Remark '' ] 887 Not , asked in the contest : A is diagonalisable since real symetric matrix it is not difficult to find its eigenvalue eigenvalues.' 4. 'The new bakery in town is offering a free sample of their famous croissants to customers who share a photo of their purchase on social media.'</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let A be an n×n matrix defined by A₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i + j for 1 ≤ i, j ≤ n. Find the rank of A.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "Step 1: Note that each entry of the matrix is given by A₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i + j, which can be written as the sum of a function of i and a function of j. In particular, write it as A₍ᵢⱼ₎ = i + j = f(i) + g(j) where f(i) = i and g(j) = j.\nStep 2: Express A as the sum of two matrices: one that depends only on the row index and one that depends only on the column index. For instance, let u be the column vector (1, 2, ..., n)ᵀ and let 1 denote the n-dimensional column vector of ones. Then the matrix u·(1)ᵀ is an n×n matrix with (i, j) entry equal to i, and similarly, 1·(u)ᵀ is an n×n matrix with (i, j) entry equal to j. Thus, A = u·(1)ᵀ + 1·(u)ᵀ.\nStep 3: Since u·(1)ᵀ is a rank 1 matrix (provided u and 1 are nonzero vectors) and 1·(u)ᵀ is also rank 1, the rank of their sum is at most 2.\nStep 4: It remains to check that these two rank-1 matrices are linearly independent when n ≥ 2. Since neither is a scalar multiple of the other (one has all rows scaled by the entries of u and the other has all columns scaled by the entries of u), their sum has rank 2 for n ≥ 2.\nStep 5: In the special case when n = 1, the 1×1 matrix A = [1+1] = [2] has rank 1.\nStep 6: Therefore, for n = 1, rank = 1 and for n ≥ 2, rank = 2.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>If n = 1, the rank of A is 1; if n ≥ 2, the rank of A is 2.</answer>"
}

